A: The error "No such file or directory" is thrown when you try to create a file in a directory that does not exist. You can create the parent directories using the mkdirs() method.
Here is an example:
File file = new File("foo/bar.txt");
try {
    file.getParentFile().mkdirs();
    file.createNewFile();
} catch (IOException e) {
    System.out.println("Something went wrong.");
}

In your second question, you are checking if the file is blank by comparing it to an empty string. This will not work because the data read from the file may contain whitespace characters. You should check if the file size is 0 to determine if it is blank.
Here is an example:
File file = new File("test.txt");
if (file.length() == 0) {
    // The file is blank
} else {
    // The file is not blank
}

If you want to check if the file is blank and then write onto it, you can use the FileInputStream to read the file and check if the file size is 0. If it is, you can write onto it. Here is an example:
File file = new File("test.txt");
if (file.length() == 0) {
    // Write onto the file
    FileOutputStream fOut = null;
    OutputStreamWriter osw = null;
    try {
        fOut = openFileOutput("test.txt", Context.MODE_PRIVATE);
        osw = new OutputStreamWriter(fOut);
        osw.write("");
        osw.close();
        fOut.close();
    } catch (Exception e) {
    }
} else {
    // The file is not blank
}

